SIMPLE: speed
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Speed
<hw>Speed</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>sp<?/d</ets>
success, swiftness, from <ets>sp<?/wan</ets> to succeed; akin to D.
<ets>spoed</ets>d, OHG. <ets>spuot</ets> success, <ets>spuot</ets> to
succees, Skr. <ets>sph⟦amac⟧</ets> to increase, grow fat.
⟦root⟧170<it>b.</it>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Prosperity in an
undertaking; favorable issue; success.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧For common
<xex>speed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O Lord God of my master Abraham, I pray thee, send me good
<qex>speed</qex> this day.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxiv. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act or state of moving swiftly; swiftness;
velocity; rapidly; rate of motion; dispatch; <as>as, the <ex>speed</ex>
a horse or a vessel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Speed</qex>, to describe whose swiftness number fails.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In kinematics, <xex>speed</xex>is sometimes used to
denote the amount of velocity without regard to direction of motion,
while <xex>velocity</xex> is not regarded as known unless both the
direction and the amount are known.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, causes or promotes speed or
success.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Hercules be thy
<xex>speed</xex>!⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>God speed</b></col>, <cd>Good speed; prosperity. See
<er>Godspeed</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Speed gauge</b></col>,
<col><b>Speed indicator</b></col>, ⟦and⟧ <col><b>Speed
recorder</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>devices for indicating
or recording the rate of a body's motion, as the number of revolutions
of a shaft in a given time.</cd> -- <col><b>Speed lathe</b></col>
<fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a power lathe with a rapidly revolving spindle,
for turning small objects, for polishing, etc.; a hand lathe.</cd> --
<col><b>Speed pulley</b></col>, <cd>a cone pulley with
steps.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Haste; swiftness; celerity; quickness; dispatch;
expedition; hurry; acceleration. See <er>Haste</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Speed
<hw>Speed</hw> <pr>(sp⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sped</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>,
<conjf>Speeded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Speeding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>sp⟦emac⟧dan</ets>, fr.
<ets>sp⟦emac⟧d</ets>, n.; akin to D. <ets>spoeden</ets>, G. sich
<ets>sputen</ets>. See <er>Speed</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To go; to fare.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To warn him now he is too farre <qex>sped</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Remedy of Love.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To experience in going; to have any condition, good
or ill; to fare.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ships heretofore in seas like fishes <qex>sped</qex>;⟦br⟧
The mightiest still upon the smallest fed.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fare well; to have success; to prosper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Save London, and send true lawyers their meed!⟦br⟧
For whoso wants money with them shall not <qex>speed</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Lydgate.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I told ye then he should prevail, and <qex>speed</qex>⟦br⟧
On his bad errand.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make haste; to move with celerity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>speeded</qex> hither with the very extremest inch of
possibility.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be expedient.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wyclif (2 Cor. xii. 1.)</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Speed
<hw>Speed</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to be
successful, or to prosper; hence, to aid; to favor.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Fortune
<xex>speed</xex> us!⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With rising gales that <qex>speed</qex> their happy flight.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to make haste; to dispatch with celerity;
to drive at full speed; hence, to hasten; to hurry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>sped</qex> him thence home to his habitation.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hasten to a conclusion; to expedite.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Judicial acts . . . are <qex>sped</qex> in open court at the
instance of one or both of the parties.</q>
<rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To hurry to destruction; to put an end to; to ruin;
to undo.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Sped</xex> with spavins.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A dire dilemma! either way I 'm <qex>sped</qex>.⟦br⟧
If foes, they write, if friends, they read, me dead.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To wish success or god fortune to, in any
undertaking, especially in setting out upon a journey.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Welcome the coming, <qex>speed</qex> the parting guest.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>God speed you</b></col>,
<col><b>them</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc., may God speed you; or, may you
have good speed.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To dispatch; hasten; expedite; accelerate;
hurry.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speed counter</ent>⟦br⟧
